{{Icelandic name|Freyja}} {{Infobox MP | honorific_prefix = | name = Freyja Haraldsdóttir | honorific_suffix = | image = | alt = | caption = | constituency = [[Southwest Constituency|Southwest]] | office = Member of the [[Althing]] | term_start = 2013 | term_end = 2015 | predecessor = <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by adding a number--> | successor = <!--Can be repeated up to 16 times by adding a number--> | prior_term = | pronunciation = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1986|06|27}} | birth_place = [[Reykjavík]], [[Iceland]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | citizenship = | nationality = | party = [[Bright Future (Iceland)|Bright Future]] | otherparty = <!--For additional political affiliations--> | height = <!-- "X cm", "X m" or "X ft Y in" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) --> | spouse = | partner = <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married--> | relations = | children = | parents = <!-- overrides mother and father parameters --> | mother = <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays "Parent(s)" as label) --> | father = <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays "Parent(s)" as label) --> | relatives = | residence = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = | profession = | known_for = | salary = | net_worth = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | cabinet = | committees = | portfolio = | awards = <!-- For civilian awards - appears as "Awards" if |mawards= is not set --> }}
'''Freyja Haraldsdóttir''' (born 27 June 1986) is an Icelandic politician and a disability rights activist. She was elected to the [[Icelandic Constitutional Assembly]] in 2010 and chosen to become a deputy Member of Parliament of the [[Althing]] in 2013.
==Early life and education== Freyja was born on 27 June 1986 in [[Reykjavík]], [[Iceland]]{{sfn|Freyja|2017|p=10}} with [[osteogenesis imperfecta]]. In 1997, Haraldsdóttir and her family moved to [[Nelson, New Zealand]] where she went to school in the neighbouring town of [[Richmond, New Zealand]].<ref name="kidson">{{cite news|last1=Kidson |first1=Sally |title=Icelandic woman changes mindsets|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/nelson-mail/news/9063777/Icelandic-woman-changes-mindsets|accessdate=23 October 2017|work=Stuff.co.nz |date=21 August 2013}}</ref> Freyja graduated from the [[University of Iceland]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[social pedagogy]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Freyja Haraldsdóttir |editor1-last=Curran|editor1-first=Tillie|editor2-last=Runswick-Cole|editor2-first=Katherine |chapter=Simply Children|title=Disabled Children's Childhood Studies: Critical Approaches in a Global Context|date=2013|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781137008220|page=13 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=8UmYAAAAQBAJ}}</ref> She continued her studies at the University of Iceland by completing a gender studies thesis for a [[Master of Arts]] degree.{{sfn|Freyja|2017|p=3}}
==Career== Before going into politics, Freyja was an advocate in support of providing people with disabilities with personal assistants. She was convinced to enter politics after meeting with former [[Bright Future (Iceland)|Bright Future party]] member [[Gudmundur Steingrimsson]] who was leading a committee that aligned with her career. In 2010, Freyja was elected onto the [[Icelandic Constitutional Assembly]]. During her term, she was selected to become Steingrimsson's deputy Member of Parliament for the [[Althing]] in 2013.<ref name="kidson"/> Her tenure of vice president for [[Southwest Constituency]] lasted from 2013 until 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Freyja Haraldsdóttir|url=https://www.althingi.is/altext/cv/is/?nfaerslunr=1188 |website=Alþingi|accessdate=25 October 2017|language=Icelandic}}</ref>
Outside of her political career, Freyja worked at [[Independent Living Centre]] from 2010 to 2014 as a director. After leaving the ILC, she co-founded the company [[Tabú]] whose goal is to create safe spaces for women with disabilities in Iceland.<ref>{{cite thesis |author=Freyja Haraldsdóttir |date=February 2017 |title=‘I am discriminated against because I exist’ |type=MA |chapter= |publisher=University of Iceland |url=https://skemman.is/bitstream/1946/26559/1/mastersthesis-FreyjaHaraldsdo%cc%81ttir.pdf |pages=12-13 |access-date=28 October 2017}}</ref>
In 2018, after her political career ended, she was subject to insults and reportedly "seal noises" by Members of Parliament who were recorded in a bar.<ref>[https://icelandmonitor.mbl.is/news/politics_and_society/2018/11/29/mp_s_in_recorded_bar_conversation_also_made_fun_of_/ Iceland Monitor, "MP's in recorded bar conversation also made fun of disabled MP"]</ref>
