'''Saba, Lady Holland''' ({{nee|Smith}}; 1802–1866) was the eldest daughter of [[Sydney Smith]] and the second wife of [[Sir Henry Holland, 1st Baronet|Sir Henry Holland]], a prominent physician and travel writer, with whom she had two daughters. She made a name for herself as the author of a much-read [[memoir]] of her famous father.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hart |first=John Seely |authorlink=John Seely Hart |date=1872 |title=A Manual of English Literature: A Text Book for Schools and Colleges |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4p8XAAAAIAAJ&q=%22lady+holland%22&pg=PA458#v=onepage |location=Philadelphia, PA |publisher=Eldredge & Brother |page=458 |accessdate=2014-08-04 }}</ref>{{efn|[https://archive.org/details/revsydneysmith01smitrich/page/n5 ''A Memoir of the Reverend Sydney Smith'', Vol. 1 (of 2)] (1856)}}

Some of Smith's often-quoted sayings were first recorded in Lady Holland's memoir, including:<blockquote>''Why, you never expected justice from a company, did you? They have neither a soul to lose, nor a body to kick.''<ref name="AndersonWaggoner2014">{{cite book|author1=James M. Anderson|author2=Ivan Waggoner|title=The Changing Role of Criminal Law in Controlling Corporate Behavior|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jCZRBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1|date=9 December 2014|publisher=Rand Corporation|isbn=978-0-8330-8786-7|pages=1–}}</ref></blockquote> and
<blockquote>''Thank God for tea! What would the world do without tea? How did it exist? I am glad I was not born before tea. I can drink any quantity when I have not tasted wine.; otherwise I am haunted by blue devils by day, and dragons by night.''<ref name="Chrystal2014">{{cite book|author=Paul Chrystal|title=Tea: A Very British Beverage|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lXYFBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT45|date=15 October 2014|publisher=Amberley Publishing Limited|isbn=978-1-4456-3360-2|pages=45–}}</ref></blockquote>

Her daughters were Caroline Holland (1834–1909; author of ''Notebooks of a Spinster Lady'', published posthumously in 1919{{efn|[https://archive.org/details/notebooksofspins00spinuoft/page/n7 ''Notebooks of a Spinster Lady''] (1919)}}) and Gertrude Holland (1840–1898).

