{{Infobox person | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Rukhl Schaechter | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1957}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | residence = [[Yonkers, New York]], United States | nationality = [[United States|American]] | alma_mater = [[Barnard]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]]), Jewish Teachers Seminary-Herzliya (B.A.), [[Bank Street College of Education]] (M.A.) | occupation = Editor of the Yiddish [[The Forward|Forverts]] | spouse = | children = 3 | father = [[Mordkhe Schaechter]] | website = }}
'''Rukhl Schaechter''' is the editor of the Yiddish [[The Forward|Forverts]], the only remaining Yiddish newspaper outside the Hasidic Jewish world.{{r|StriglerObit}} She is the first woman, the first person born in the [[United States]], and likely the first [[Shomer Shabbat|Sabbath observant Jew]] to hold that position.{{r|BoulderJN}}{{r|Tablet}}
== Early life and education == Shaechter comes from a long line of Yiddishists as part of the [[Schaechter-Gottesman]] family:{{r|honeyandschmaltz}} her father, [[Mordkhe Schaechter]], was a [[Yiddish]] linguist who devoted his life to studying and teaching the language in the United States,{{r|NYTObitMordkhe}} while her aunt was Yiddish poet and songwriter [[Beyle Schaechter-Gottesman]].{{r|YiddishBookCenter}} She was raised in a small Yiddish speaking community in [[The Bronx]].{{r|Barnard}} She completed a bachelor's degree in psychology at [[Barnard College]] in 1979,{{r|Barnard}}, and then studied at Jewish Teachers Seminary in Herzliya and [[Bank Street College of Education]].{{r|Tablet}} She became an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jew]] as an adult.{{r|Tablet}}
== Career == Shaechter was working as a Yiddish teacher at a Jewish school in New York--and a prizewinning writer of Yiddish short stories and songs--when she was recruited to join Forverts as reporter in 1998.{{r|Tablet}}{{r|BoulderJN}}{{r|Barnard}} In 2016, she was named editor of the paper.{{r|Tablet}} During her time at Forverts, the newspaper has increased its online presence and its outreach to people whose ancestors spoke Yiddish but are not fluent in the language themselves, including cooking videos in Yiddish and videos with English subtitles.{{r|Tablet}}{{r|Jewniverse}} It has also increased outreach to [[Hasidic Judaism|Hasidic Jewish]] readers and writers, who use in a different alphabetization of Yiddish than the [[YIVO]] standard alphabetization generally used by the paper.{{r|Tablet}} She has brought new Yiddish writers to the paper, including women from both secular and Hasidic backgrounds.{{r|BoulderJN}}{{r|ForwardBio}}
