{{infobox ethnic group | group = Wachaprague people | population = Extinct as a tribe | popplace = [[Tidewater region of Virginia|Coastal]] [[Virginia]] | rels = [[Native religion]] | langs = [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]] | related = }}
The '''Wachapreague''' people were an [[Algonquian peoples|Algonquian]] [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] people who lived in coastal [[Virginia]] centuries ago.
The town of [[Wachapreague, Virginia]], and the [[Wachapreague Channel]] are named for them.
Captain [[John Smith (explorer)|John Smith]] reported contact with these Indians.<ref>{{cite book|author=Federal Writers' Project|title=The Ocean Highway: New Brunswick, New Jersey to Jacksonville, Florida|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015064565875;view=1up;seq=125|year=1938|publisher=Works Progress Administration|page=73}}</ref>
